snippet.title: Hard Drive Platter Extraction... #technology
snippet.description:
In this video, we work on a Seagate ST5000LM000 drive that was originally enclosed in a Seagate Backup Plus external hard drive.

This drive had previously been worked on by another company and suffered from stiction, where one of the read/write heads became stuck to the platter surface. To recover the data, we had to carefully remove the platters, free the stuck head, and resolve several firmware issues.

After a detailed repair process, we were able to successfully extract our customer‚Äôs data.

snippet.title: LDR Color Checker
snippet.description:
Diagram, Code and 3D Model HERE:
https://hackmakemod.com/blogs/projects/ldr-color-checker

This project turns a simple Light Dependent Resistor (LDR) into a surprisingly accurate color checker. By pulsing an addressable LED through red, green, and blue, the sensor measures how much light is reflected from a surface. Each color creates a unique reflection pattern that the code matches to the closest color name‚Ä¶ all in less than a quarter of a second!

With just a 10k LDR, a microcontroller, a button, and a small display, the setup delivers results that feel way beyond the simplicity of the parts. A custom shroud ensures the LDR only sees reflected light, making the readings reliable. Orange, for example, reflects strong red but weaker green and blue, which makes it easy for the code to recognize.

It‚Äôs proof that even basic sensors can be pushed to do much more than you might expect.

https://hackmakemod.com/blogs/projects/ldr-color-checker

This project turns a simple Light Dependent Resistor (LDR) into a surprisingly accurate color checker. By pulsing an addressable LED through red, green, and blue, the sensor measures how much light is reflected from a surface. Each color creates a unique reflection pattern that the code matches to the closest color name‚Ä¶ all in less than a quarter of a second!

With just a 10k LDR, a microcontroller, a button, and a small display, the setup delivers results that feel way beyond the simplicity of the parts. A custom shroud ensures the LDR only sees reflected light, making the readings reliable. Orange, for example, reflects strong red but weaker green and blue, which makes it easy for the code to recognize.

It‚Äôs proof that even basic sensors can be pushed to do much more than you might expect.

snippet.title: I built my own Phone... because innovation is sad rn
snippet.description:
Big thanks to PCBway, let them help bring your projects to life! https://www.pcbway.com/

With many Samsung zFlip phones hitting the unfortunate fate of a broken folding screen, I took it as an opportunity to build my own silly phone. Taking only the minimum parts required for the phone to function, I redesigned the entire enclosure for a *slightly* different CNC machined aluminum one. I split the two halves, added a four bar linkage for a flip out action, and of course; I added a BlackBerry keyboard to the internals. With an Arduino pro micro inside emulating a USB keyboard, this wacky  smartphone now has a permanent physical keyboard, you can flip out on demand. A truly modern take on a flip phone in my opinion. 

More project details: https://www.pcbway.com/project/shareproject/A_Modified_zFlip_5_969c2c62.html

Thank you so much for watching and I hope you enjoyed.

Join the Discord! https://discord.gg/G8PuBAgaRZ

snippet.title: HP Scammed Us: HP Omen 45L is the Worst Pre-Built We've Reviewed
snippet.description:
Sponsor: Lian Li Lancool 217 on Amazon https://geni.us/0dwg
The HP Omen 45L is the worst pre-built gaming PC we have ever benchmarked and reviewed. The system not only has unbelievably bad thermals for its "cryochamber" for the 50 seconds it actually runs at the Intel guidance, but it also kneecaps performance after 50 seconds to make the 285K be worse than the 265K in all-core workloads. Fixing this issue requires the user to acknowledge voiding their warranty, and that's not to mention the spyware and bloatware shoved into this expensive gaming computer.

snippet.description:
Introducing the "VitalWear SmartBand," a next-generation wearable gadget that combines health monitoring, productivity tools, and entertainment features in a sleek, minimalist design. It features a flexible OLED display that wraps around the wrist, providing a comfortable fit and immersive visual experience. The SmartBand tracks vital signs Like heart rate, blood oxygen Levels, and body temperature in real-time, using advanced sensors and Al algorithms to provide personalized health insights and alerts.



Beyond health tracking, the VitalWear SmartBand integrates with your digital Life, offering seamless notifications, voice assistant support, and quick access to your schedule, reminders, and messages. It also includes a built-in mini projector that can display images or presentations on any flat surface, perfect for on-the-go professionals. Additionally, the SmartBand supports wireless charging and has a battery life of up to 10 days making it a versatile and essential gadget for modern Life
